The paper proposes an approach to preference elicitation that involves iteratively collecting feedback from users and dynamically extending the feature space based on user critiques. This approach is suited for constructive learning tasks where the option catalogue is generated on-the-fly. The paper also presents an upper bound on the average regret suffered by the learner. Based on these characteristics, the most likely arXiv CS sub-categories are cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also involves aspects of human-computer interaction (cs.HC), information retrieval (cs.IR), and cybersecurity (cs.CY) as it deals with user feedback and feature space extension.
